Topology is the branch of mathematics that studies patterns of geometric figures involving position and relative position without regard to size. From the very beginning, topology has evolved under the influence of questions arising from the attempt to understand properties of "singular" spaces. Singular spaces are usually not quite manifolds (i.e., regular), as they may possess "singularities", but they are comprised of manifold layers, the "strata". Such spaces occur naturally in various fields of pure mathematics including geometric topology and algebraic geometry, and also in more applied fields, such as computational topology, biology, or physics. In recent years, there has been extensive interest and success in expanding to singular spaces the triumphs of manifold theory.

This award provided participant travel support for a conference on "Stratified spaces in geometric and computational topology and physics" held at the University of Wisconsin in Madison, WI, during March 30 - April 2, 2015, as well as for two follow-up workshops on the Topology of Singularities, held at UW-Madison in 2016 and 2017. These events brought together researchers and students interested in the topological study of singular algebraic varieties, topological data analysis, and interactions between knot theory, algebraic geometry and mathematical physics. The events, while intended to disseminate recent developments, also had a significant educational component, featuring introductory lectures at a level accessible to graduate students, as well as discussion sessions to strengthen connections among the various research groups represented. Furthermore, the conference and workshops funded by this award provided ideal opportunities for junior researchers, postdoctoral associates, graduate students and members of under-represented groups to broaden their perspectives and to create research ties with more senior members in these fields.

The events funded by this award featured lectures on the following topics, each driven by recent and fundamental advances:

(1) Codimension two embedding theory and hypersurface singularities;

(2) Topology of stratified maps;

(3) Hodge-theoretic aspects of singularities;

(4) Characteristic classes of singular varieties;

(5) Singular spaces in mathematical physics;

(6) Stratified spaces in computational topology.

These topics intersect a broad range of research endeavors in fields ranging from pure mathematics to more applied areas, thus conference participants reflected a broad cross-section of mathematical disciplines.

In recent decades, the basic tools involved in the study of singular stratified spaces have branched out into a myriad of mathematical territories, and it increasingly becomes important to provide opportunities, such as these events, for experts in the various related specializations to interact. 

